ODE VI.

ln this beautiful ode the poet does not merely describe the pleasures and charms of Spring. His object seems to be to in- culcate a moral lesson. He would show by the rapid succes- sion of the seasons, and the decay of all things in the vegetable kingdom, that man himself is rapidly passing away3 and that whatever he has to do in this life must be done quickly.

ODE VII.

This ode is supposed to have been written either at the time of the Saturnalia, when it was customary among the Romans to send presents to their friends; or in return for something valuable which the poet had received from Censorinus3 for which he sent him these verses. So poets have usually paid their debts of gratitudo.
